# TypeScript Best Practices

## Type Safety

- Always use explicit return types on exported functions and class methods.
- Prefer `interface` over `type` for object shapes that may be extended; use `type` for unions and intersections.
- Never use `any` — use `unknown` and narrow with type guards, or use precise generics.
- Avoid non-null assertions (`!`) unless you can prove null is impossible; prefer optional chaining (`?.`) and nullish coalescing (`??`).
- Use `const` for all variable declarations unless mutation is required.

## Generics

- Name generic parameters descriptively when context is unclear (`TElement`, `TConfig`), single letters (`T`, `K`, `V`) only in well-known patterns (Array, Map).
- Constrain generics appropriately (`T extends SomeBase`) rather than leaving them unconstrained.

## Naming Conventions

- PascalCase for types, interfaces, enums, and React components.
- camelCase for variables, functions, and object properties.
- SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE for module-level constants that are truly immutable values.
- Boolean variables and props should start with `is`, `has`, `can`, or `should`.

## Enums & Unions

- Prefer string literal unions (`"loading" | "success" | "error"`) over enums for small fixed sets.
- Use regular `enum` (not `const enum`) when you need runtime reverse-lookup; `const enum` values are inlined at compile-time and do not exist in JavaScript output, so they cannot be reverse-mapped at runtime.

## How to Verify

1. Run `yarn test:typecheck` — zero TypeScript errors expected.
2. Run `yarn test:code` (ESLint) — no `@typescript-eslint/no-explicit-any` violations.
3. Open any exported function in `packages/excalidraw/src` and confirm it has an explicit return type.
4. Search for `as any` occurrences: `grep -r "as any" packages/ --include="*.ts" --include="*.tsx"` — should return zero results.
